Interface Component

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<Component>, LocaleContextSource
    All Known Subinterfaces:

    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractButton, AbstractLazyInit, AbstractSimpleValueEditor, BooleanValueEditor, Calendar, CalendarDateRange, CardContainer, Checkbox, ClickToEditComponent, ClickToEditForm, CollapsibleContainer, ComboBox, ComboBoxValueEditor, ComponentImpl, Container, CountryInformationRenderer, CustomCellRenderer, DateComponent, DateFormatLabel, Dialog, DoubleEntryField, EmptyTableHider, Field, FileField, Frame, HistoryContainer, HTMLComponent, Image, Label, ListComponent, LocaleSelector, LocalizationRenderer, LocalizedNamedObjectRenderer, LocalizedObjectKeyFieldComponent, LocalizedTextEditor, Media, Menu, MenuItem, MessageContainer, MTable, MTree, NumberEditor, OptionallyLocalizedNamedObjectRenderer, OptionDialog, Pager, PopupMenu, ProgrammaticIdentifierEditor, PushButton, RadioButton, ResetButton, RichList, SearchableComboBox, SearchUIImpl, Separator, TabbedContainerImpl, Table, Tabs, TextButton, TextEditor, ToggleButton, Tree, URILink, Window, WindowContainer

    public interface Component
extends LocaleContextSource, Iterable<Component>
    Base interface for all user interface objects. The Component class provides the basic methods needed to handle a user interface component.
    Author:
    Russ Tennant (russ@i2rd.com)

      • canClose

        boolean canClose()
        Determines if the component can be closed. Components that have user editable state should return false if the object has decided the user must take some action before closing. Returning false does not guarantee the component will not be closed. An operation that forces the component to be closed regardless of the value this method returns is possible.
        Returns:
        true if the component can close.

           throws CannotCloseMIWTException

      • getHTMLElement

        Element getHTMLElement()
        Get the top level elements this component will output in its current state. This should not included the entire content model.

        For example, if your code outputs the following, <p><span><b></b></span></p>, then you should only return one element that is a "p"; NOT "p, span, b".

        All configuration elements should be nested within this top element, or other arrangements should be made with the inner keeper.

        Returns:
        the element.

      • init

        void init()

        Called when a Component is first attached to a WindowManager. This means the Component should have valid return values from getApplication(), getLocaleContext(), getParent(). It is preferable to have all construction of the Component go here since a valid LocaleContext, Application object, etc., are available.

        When overriding this method, be sure to call the super class init(). init() is called only once for each Component. The parent component will have been init()ed before init() is called.

        NOTE: Do not call this method from application code. It is meant to be called by the WindowManager only.

      • preRenderProcess

        void preRenderProcess(Request request,
                    Response response,
                    RendererEditorState<?> state)
        Allow the component to process any form fields before rendering. This method must be called by subclasses. Method calls on components, creating or destroying components, or nearly everything else having to do with the component tree and related data models must be done by queuing an event using EventQueue.queue(EventQueueElement). Otherwise you may get unexpected results.
        Parameters:
        request - the request.
        response - the response.
        state - the renderer / editor state, will be null if not using as a renderer / editor.

        void putClientProperty(Object key,
                     Object value)
        Adds an arbitrary key/value "client property" to the component. Each component has a per-instance map where properties can be stored. If the value is null, the property is removed.
        Parameters:
        key - The key for the property.
        value - The value for the property.

      • removeFromParent

        void removeFromParent()

        INTERNAL Use - intended to only be called by Component implementors.

        Removes this component from its parent. This method is different from detach() in that it calls the parent component to remove so that internal fields are updated.

      • setEnabled

        void setEnabled(boolean b)
        Check if the component should be enabled. An enabled component can receive input, a disabled component does not receive input but may be displayed if isVisible() returns true. If the parent component is disabled, so will this component be disabled. If the parent becomes enabled and this component was previously set to enabled, it becomes enabled when the parent is set to enabled.
        Parameters:
        b - true to enable for input.

      • stateRequested

        void stateRequested(Map<String,String> state)

        Called to request the component to setup a given state. The state is given by a map of String to String. This method is normally called in response to an application state event to give the component an opportunity to handle itself. This method will call the method of the same name in any child components.

        When overriding this method it is important to call this method (i.e. super.stateRequested(state)) after handling the request. If components are created or removed in this method then the child components to be considered should be after this behavior, therefore calling super.stateRequested(state) last.

        NOTE: Do NOT modify the state map. It is used by other components in the tree and modifying it may produce undesirable behavior.

        Parameters:
        state - The state map.

      • validate

        void validate()

        Normally called by the medium to make sure the component is in a valid state before updating the medium. Other classes may safely call as needed. Note however that validating may take a substantial amount of work depending on the subclass implementation!.

        NOTE: When overriding this method, be sure to call the super class validate() as the last statement in the overridden method.
